<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1059,350,460]" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2010" box="[459,595,350,371]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Megaphloeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="985" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[459,595,350,371]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">Megaphloeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2011 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[861,996,350,372]" pageId="26" pageNumber="985" pagination="63 - 132" refId="ref53182" refString="OPITZ W. (2011 a): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the Epiphloeinae (Coleoptera: Cleridae). Part IX. The genus Megaphloeus OPITZ, 2010. - Entomologica Basiliensia et Collectionis Frey 33: 63 - 132." type="journal article" year="2011">OPITZ 2011a</bibRefCitation>
). This work included a key to species. 
<taxonomicName box="[520,767,379,400]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Megaphloeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="985" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imparilus">
<emphasis box="[520,767,379,400]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">Megaphloeus imparilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens key out to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">M. animosus</emphasis>
(WOLCOTT), from which 
<taxonomicName box="[525,660,409,430]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Megaphloeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="985" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imparilus">
<emphasis box="[525,660,409,430]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">M. imparilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing a more angular midelytral fascia and the antenna are more strongly sex dimorphic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1059,475,820]" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,475,497]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.3" pageId="26" pageNumber="985" unit="mm" value="5.3">5.3 mm</quantity>
; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,475,497]" captionStart="Figs 298-301" captionStartId="102.[151,191,1516,1538]" captionTargetBox="[154,1059,202,1504]" captionTargetId="figure@102.[153,1059,202,1504]" captionTargetPageId="102" captionText="Figs 298-301: Habitus; (298) Madoniella nota; (299) M. selvanegra; (300) Megaphloeus imparilus; (301) M. yasuni." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746810/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">Fig. 300</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium and pronotum dark castaneous; antennae tricolorous, scape testaceous, fundus castaneous, capitulum black; pterothorax black; elytra mostly dark brown, inverted Tshaped flavotestaceous humeral macula poorly defined; legs testaceous; abdomen brown; mesoscutellum dark brown. Head: Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[618,695,593,615]" captionStart="Figs 43-60" captionStartId="72.[151,191,1361,1383]" captionTargetBox="[157,1053,222,1351]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[152,1057,206,1351]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="Figs 43-60: Antennae; (43) Ordinis taxis; (44) Pelonium tayrona; (45) Neorthopleura turnbowi, male; (46) N. turnbowi, female; (47) Megaphloeus imparilus; (48) Plocamocera catalexis; (48 a) Cregya entrerios; (49) Ridica merida. (50) Kataspinula puebla. (51) Cregya tobagoensis; (52) Topainca patchacutii; (53) Eurycaulis anaxeis; (54) Amboakis expandosa. (55) Ridica achira. (56) Ampleris cacuminis; (57) Sicamus suprus; (58) Sirpa latiflava; (59) Alarius careoritus; (60) Cregya petalosa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746750" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746750/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
) capitate, sex dimorphic, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter towards capitulum, capitular antennomeres 9 and 10 triangular, in male antennomere 11 oblong, nearly twice as long as antennomere 10; eyes large, finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 15/30). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[233,322,710,732]" captionStart="Figs 179-193" captionStartId="81.[151,191,1359,1381]" captionTargetBox="[167,1032,201,1342]" captionTargetId="figure@81.[152,1058,201,1346]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="Figs 179-193: Pronota; 179) Phonius versus; (180) Perilypus arsus; (181) A. nodus; (182) Pyticara frontegalba; (183) Pelonium implacide; (184) Neorthoplera quintana; (185) Perilypus virgulatus; (186) P. alpinus; (187) Amboakis expandosa; (188) Ampleris jatai; (189) Megaphloeus jasuni; (190) Amboakis bermejo (191) Madoniella delta; (192) Megaphloeus imparilus; (193) Pyticeroides brevitubulus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746768/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">Fig. 192</figureCitation>
) transverse; pronotal arch transversally wrinkled (PW/PL 70/55), disc deeply concave paralaterally near pronotal collar; elytral asetiferous punctures profusely distributed; (EL/EW 250/75); anterior margin of protibia with 6 spines. Abdomen: Pygidium quadrate 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[343,350,798,820]" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[613,701,798,820]" captionStart="Figs 225-230" captionStartId="87.[151,191,1270,1292]" captionTargetBox="[150,1058,198,1255]" captionTargetId="figure@87.[150,1058,198,1255]" captionTargetPageId="87" captionText="Figs 225-230: Aedeagi; (225) Madoniella selvanegra; (226) Megaphloeus imparilus; (227) Pyticeroides brevitubulus; (228) Kataspinula puebla; (229) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (230) N. cuspidis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746780" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746780/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">Fig. 226</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1058,835,916]" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">
Variation: The available specimens are quite homogeneous, except that the last antennomere is sex-dimorphic, with the male 11 
<superScript attach="left" box="[666,679,861,875]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">th</superScript>
antennomere much longer than the female 11 
<superScript attach="left" box="[252,265,890,904]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="985">th</superScript>
antennomere.
</paragraph>
